Method Detail

getSymbol

String getSymbol()
Returns the publicly known symbol this instrument. Mostly used for display purposes.

getRicRoot

String getRicRoot()
Returns the technical code for this instrument. For futures, this is the root code, which needs to be appended with expiry information to become unique across all underlying futures contracts. For other other types of instruments, this is a unique code.

getFactor

int getFactor()
Returns the factor between the quoted price and the notional value of the handled contract. For example, when requesting to buy 1 Crude Oil future (factor of 1000, or 1000 barrels per contract), valued at 75$ per barrel, the notional amount is 1x1000x$75=$75,000.

This value is typically 1 for stocks and indices. However, it can vary greatly for futures.

This value is not relevant to instruments that are not Tradeable, but it is more convenient for writing a strategy to have it defined in this interface.

getTickSize

double getTickSize(double price)
Returns the tick size for the instrument. For some stocks, tick size depends on the value of the stock, which explains why a price is expected in parameter.

This value is not relevant to instruments that are not Tradeable, but it is more convenient for writing a strategy to have it defined in this interface.

Parameters:
price - the value of the instrument, for cases where the tick size depends on it; for instruments for which a tick size does not make sense (such as Currencies and Indices), this value should not be consider reliable

getStandardMarketHours

StandardMarketHours getStandardMarketHours()
Returns the time when the instrument is being traded. These are the official trading times; trades sometimes occur outside those hours, but they are not returned when backtesting a strategy.

getAfterInvalidDataDate

org.joda.time.DateTime getAfterInvalidDataDate()
Returns the date from which trades for this instrument are read. There might not always be trades immediately after this date; instead, it should be understood at meaning "data before this date are known to be invalid".

This value is mostly used for some particular stocks where old trades are available, but contain incorrect values. For other instruments, it is simply the default first date.
